    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-02-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="5"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d5">
                <head>5. Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> to
                    Professor <persName corresp="#p_SAA_1">Andrei Sakharov</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d5fn1">Source: Department of State, Files of
                        the Bureau of European Affairs, Office of Soviet Union Affairs, Lot 91D231,
                        Box 3, Old <persName corresp="#p_SAA_1">Sakharov</persName> Files,
                        1975–1978. No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-02-05">February 5, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Professor <persName corresp="#p_SAA_1"
                        >Sakharov</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I received your letter of January 21,<note n="2" xml:id="d5fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d2">Document 2</ref>.</note> and I want to express my
                    appreciation to you for bringing your thoughts to my personal attention.</p>
                <p>Human rights is a central concern of my Administration. In my inaugural address I
                    stated: “Because we are free, we can never be indifferent to the fate of freedom
                        elsewhere.”<note n="3" xml:id="d5fn3">See <ref target="#d3fn2">footnote 2,
                            Document 3</ref>.</note> You may rest assured that the American people
                    and our government will continue our firm commitment to promote respect for
                    human rights not only in our own country but also abroad.</p>
                <p>We shall use our good offices to seek the release of prisoners of conscience, and
                    we will continue our efforts to shape a world responsive to human aspirations in
                    which nations of differing cultures and histories can live side by side in peace
                    and justice.</p>
                <p>I am always glad to hear from you, and I wish you well.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Jimmy Carter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
